faqs:
  - q: "What is a step-up (top-up) SIP?"
    a: >-
      A step-up SIP automatically increases your monthly instalment at a fixed interval, usually once a year, by a percentage or fixed amount you choose. Most fund houses and platforms let you set this when starting the SIP, so your investment keeps pace with salary increments without any manual effort.
  - q: "How much difference does a 10% annual step-up make?"
    a: >-
      A large one. A flat ₹10,000 SIP at 12% for 20 years grows to about ₹92 lakh, while the same SIP stepped up 10% every year reaches roughly ₹1.85 crore — about twice the corpus — because your contributions compound from a bigger base each year.
  - q: "Is a step-up SIP better than starting with a bigger SIP?"
    a: >-
      If you can afford the bigger amount today, starting bigger is mathematically better because money invested earlier compounds longer. The step-up is for the realistic case where your surplus grows with your income — it commits your future increments in advance, which is easier than finding a large amount now.
  - q: "Can I add a step-up to an existing SIP?"
    a: >-
      Many platforms do not allow editing an existing SIP's step-up. The common workaround is to either register a fresh SIP for the incremental amount each year, or cancel and re-register the SIP with the step-up facility enabled. Neither affects your existing units.
  - q: "What step-up percentage should I choose?"
    a: >-
      Match it to your expected salary growth, typically 5–10% a year in India. The key is sustainability: a 10% step-up doubles your instalment in about 7 years, so make sure the committed amounts remain comfortable alongside your other goals.
